Reference-contexts: When the mind is focused on one piece of information, it jumps instantly to the next that is suggested by the association of thoughts, in accordance with some intricate web of trails carried by the cells of the brain <ref> (Bush 1945) </ref>. With the web, hypertext allows one particular page to contain multiple links to other pages. A user merely clicks on one of these hyperlinks and is easily transported to the related page. This allows for a trail to be forged through the vast information space of the web. <p> The trail history of a Persona captures some of the thought and understanding which went into a particular searching or browsing session of the author and intends to communicate this to a viewer <ref> (Bush 1945) </ref>. As one browses the web, one does not usually jump randomly from one page anywhere on the web to another unrelated page. A browsing session (a sequence of web pages) is usually very logical, and viewing the browsing session of another user can be very informative.
